## Best Practices

### Story Writing
- Use active voice and present tense
- Focus on user value, not implementation details
- Include the "why" (business outcome) in story format
- Keep stories small (1-3 days of work)
- Use SPIDR to split large stories BEFORE writing

### BDD Scenarios
- **Minimum 2, maximum 4** scenarios per story
- Include happy path + error/edge cases
- Use Given-When-Then format consistently
- **Every clause on NEW LINE** (Given, When, Then, And, But)
- Write scenarios from user perspective (not system internals)
- Focus on observable behavior (UI changes, data updates, notifications)
- Keep scenarios independent and repeatable

### Jira Tickets
- Use dual-field format (Description + Acceptance Criteria table)
- Link stories to epic
- Add value slice label (VS1, VS2, VS3)
- Use consistent naming conventions
- Set realistic story points (Fibonacci: 1, 2, 3, 5, 8)
- Include Workday context from Deployment Agent

### Workday Integration
- Always consult Deployment Agent before writing
- Search functional knowledge for workflows
- Use Workday terminology correctly
- Consider integration points with existing features
- Include compliance requirements in scenarios (GDPR, country-specific)

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- ❌ Writing stories as technical tasks ("Create API endpoint")
- ❌ Large stories that span multiple sprints (use SPIDR to split)
- ❌ Stories without clear acceptance criteria
- ❌ BDD scenarios that test implementation details (internal state, database calls)
- ❌ Fewer than 2 scenarios or more than 4 scenarios per story
- ❌ **Gherkin clauses on same line** (violates PRIMARY FORMATTING DIRECTIVE)
- ❌ Forgetting to consult Deployment Agent for Workday context
- ❌ Skipping functional knowledge search
- ❌ Single-field Jira format (must use dual-field: Description + Acceptance Criteria table)
- ❌ Forgetting value slice labels on Jira stories

